#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Layers of abstraction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:175
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The block devices above represent an abstract interface to the disk. User\n"
"programs can use these block devices to interact with your disk without\n"
"worrying about whether your drivers are IDE, SCSI, or something else. The\n"
"program can simply address the storage on the disk as a bunch of contiguous,\n"
"randomly-accessible 512-byte blocks. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:185
#, no-wrap
msgid "Partitions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:189
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Under Linux, we create filesystems by using a special command called\n"
"<c>mkfs</c> (or <c>mke2fs</c>, <c>mkreiserfs</c>, etc.), specifying a\n"
"particular block device as a command-line argument.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:195
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, although it is theoretically possible to use a \"whole disk\" block\n"
"device (one that represents the entire disk) like <path>/dev/hda</path> or\n"
"<path>/dev/sda</path> to house a single filesystem, this is almost never done\n"
"in practice. Instead, full disk block devices are split up into smaller, more\n"
"manageable block devices called partititons. Partitions are created using a\n"
"tool called <c>fdisk</c>, which is used to create and edit the partition table\n"
"that's stored on each disk. The partition table defines exactly how to split up\n"
"the full disk.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:208
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing fdisk"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:212
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We can take a look at a disk's partition table by running <c>fdisk</c>,\n"
"specifying a block device that represents a full disk as an argument.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:217
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Alternate interfaces to the disk's partition table include <c>cfdisk</c>,\n"
"<c>parted</c>, and <c>partimage</c>. I recommend that you avoid using\n"
"<c>cfdisk</c> (despite what the fdisk manual page may say) because it sometimes\n"
"calculates disk geometry incorrectly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:223
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using fdisk on IDE drive"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:224
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>fdisk /dev/hda</i>\n"
