#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:284
#, no-wrap
msgid "Block device and partitioning overview"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:288
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Notice the name of the corresponding partition block devices on the left side,\n"
"starting with <path>/dev/hda1</path> and going up to <path>/dev/hda9</path>. In\n"
"the early days of the PC, partitioning software only allowed a maximum of four\n"
"partitions (called primary partitions). This was too limiting, so a workaround\n"
"called extended partitioning was created. An extended partition is very similar\n"
"to a primary partition, and counts towards the primary partition limit of four.\n"
"However, extended partitions can hold any number of so-called logical\n"
"partitions inside them, providing an effective means of working around the four\n"
"partition limit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:302
#, no-wrap
msgid "Partitioning overview, continued"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:306
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"All partitions hda5 and higher are logical partitions. The numbers 1 through 4\n"
"are reserved for primary or extended partitions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:311
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In our example, hda1 through hda3 are primary partitions. hda4 is an extended\n"
"partition that contains logical partitions hda5 through hda9. You would never\n"
"actually use <path>/dev/hda4</path> for storing any filesystems directly -- it\n"
"simply acts as a container for partitions hda5 through hda9.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:320
#, no-wrap
msgid "Partition types"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:324
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Also, notice that each partition has an \"Id,\" also called a partition type.\n"
"Whenever you create a new partition, you should ensure that the partition type\n"
"is set correctly. 83 is the correct partition type for partitions that will be\n"
"housing Linux filesystems, and 82 is the correct partition type for Linux swap\n"
"partitions. You set the partition type using the t option in <c>fdisk</c>. The\n"
"Linux kernel uses the partition type setting to auto-detect fileystems and swap\n"
"devices on the disk at boot-time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:336
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using fdisk to set up partitions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:340
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that you've had your introduction to the way disk partitioning is done\n"
"under Linux, it's time to walk through the process of setting up disk\n"
"partitions and filesystems for a new Linux installation. In this process, we\n"
"will configure a disk with new partitions and then create filesystems on them.\n"
"These steps will provide us with a completely clean disk with no data on it\n"
"that can then be used as a basis for a new Linux installation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:349
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To follow these steps, you need to have a hard drive that does not contain any\n"
"important data, since these steps will <e>erase</e> the data on your disk. If\n"
"this is all new to you, you may want to consider just reading the steps, or\n"
"using a Linux boot disk on a test system so that no data will be at risk.\n"
msgstr ""

