#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:640
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating filesystems"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:644
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that the partitions have been created, it's time to set up filesystems on\n"
"the boot and root partitions so that they can be mounted and used to store\n"
"data. We will also configure the swap partition to serve as swap storage.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:650
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linux supports a variety of different types of filesystems; each type has its\n"
"strengths and weaknesses and its own set of performance characteristics. We\n"
"will cover the creation of ext2, ext3, XFS, JFS, and ReiserFS filesystems in\n"
"this tutorial. Before we create filesystems on our example system, let's\n"
"briefly review the various filesystems available under Linux. We'll go into\n"
"more detail on the filesystems later in the tutorial.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:661
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1250
#, no-wrap
msgid "The ext2 filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:665
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ext2 is the tried-and-true Linux filesystem, but it doesn't have metadata\n"
"journaling, which means that routine ext2 filesystem checks at startup time can\n"
"be quite time-consuming. There is now quite a selection of newer-generation\n"
"journaled filesystems that can be checked for consistency very quickly and are\n"
"thus generally preferred over their non-journaled counterparts. Journaled\n"
"filesystems prevent long delays when you boot your system and your filesystem\n"
"happens to be in an inconsistent state.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:677
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1275
#, no-wrap
msgid "The ext3 filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:681
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ext3 is the journaled version of the ext2 filesystem, providing metadata\n"
"journaling for fast recovery in addition to other enhanced journaling modes,\n"
"such as full data and ordered data journaling. ext3 is a very good and reliable\n"
"filesystem. It offers generally decent performance under most conditions.\n"
"Because it does not extensively employ the use of \"trees\" in its internal\n"
"design, it doesn't scale very well, meaning that it is not an ideal choice for\n"
"very large filesystems or situations where you will be handling very large\n"
"files or large quantities of files in a single directory. But when used within\n"
"its design parameters, ext3 is an excellent filesystem.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:693
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One of the nice things about ext3 is that an existing ext2 filesystem can be\n"
"upgraded \"in-place\" to ext3 quite easily. This allows for a seamless upgrade\n"
"path for existing Linux systems that are already using ext2.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:701
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1344
#, no-wrap
msgid "The ReiserFS filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:705
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ReiserFS is a B-tree-based filesystem that has very good overall performance\n"
"and greatly outperforms both ext2 and ext3 when dealing with small files (files\n"
"less than 4k), often by a factor of 10x-15x. ReiserFS also scales extremely\n"
"well and has metadata journaling. As of kernel 2.4.18+, ReiserFS is now\n"
"rock-solid and highly recommended for use both as a general-purpose filesystem\n"
"and for extreme cases such as the creation of large filesystems, the use of\n"
"many small files, very large files, and directories containing tens of\n"
"thousands of files. ReiserFS is the filesystem we recommend by default for all\n"
"non-boot partitions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:719
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1382
#, no-wrap
msgid "The XFS filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:723
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"XFS is a filesystem with metadata journaling. It comes with a robust\n"
"feature-set and is optimized for scalability. We only recommend using this\n"
"filesystem on Linux systems with high-end SCSI and/or fibre channel storage and\n"
"a uninterruptible power supply. Because XFS aggressively caches in-transit data\n"
"in RAM, improperly designed programs (those that don't take proper precautions\n"
"when writing files to disk (and there are quite a few of them) can lose a good\n"
"deal of data if the system goes down unexpectedly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:735
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1422
#, no-wrap
msgid "The JFS filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:739
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"JFS is IBM's own high performance journaling filesystem. It has recently become\n"
"production-ready, and we would like to see a longer track record before\n"
"commenting either positively nor negatively on its general stability at this\n"
"point.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:748
#, no-wrap
msgid "Filesystem recommendations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:752
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're looking for the most rugged journaling filesystem, use ext3. If\n"
"you're looking for a good general-purpose high-performance filesystem with\n"
"journaling support, use ReiserFS; both ext3 and ReiserFS are mature, refined\n"
"and recommended for general use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:759
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Based on our example above, we will use the following commands to initialize\n"
"all our partitions for use:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:763
#, no-wrap
msgid "Initlizing partitions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:764
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>mke2fs -j /dev/hda1</i>\n"
"# <i>mkswap /dev/hda2</i>\n"
"# <i>mkreiserfs /dev/hda3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:770
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We choose ext3 for our <path>/dev/hda1</path> boot partition because it is a\n"
"robust journaling filesystem supported by all major boot loaders. We used\n"
"<c>mkswap</c> for our <path>/dev/hda2</path> swap partition -- the choice is\n"
"obvious here. And for our main root filesystem on <path>/dev/hda3</path> we\n"
"choose ReiserFS, since it is a solid journaling filesystem offering excellent\n"
"performance. Now, go ahead and initialize your partitions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:781
#, no-wrap
msgid "Making swap"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:785
#, no-wrap
msgid "<c>mkswap</c> is the command that used to initialize swap partitions:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:788
#, no-wrap
msgid "Initalizing swap partition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:789
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mkswap /dev/hda2</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:793
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Unlike regular filesystems, swap partitions aren't mounted. Instead, they are\n"
"enabled using the <c>swapon</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:797
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling swap partition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:798
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>swapon /dev/hdc6</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:802
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Your Linux system's startup scripts will take care of automatically enabling\n"
"your swap partitions. Therefore, the <c>swapon</c> command is generally only\n"
"needed when you need to immediately add some swap that you just created. To\n"
"view the swap devices currently enabled, type <c>cat /proc/swaps</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:811
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating ext2, ext3, and ReiserFS filesystems"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:815
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can use the <c>mke2fs</c> command to create ext2 filesystems:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:818
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating ext2 filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:819
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mke2fs /dev/hda1</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:823
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you would like to use ext3, you can create ext3 filesystems using <c>mke2fs\n"
"-j</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:827
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating ext3 filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:828
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mke2fs /dev/hda3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:832
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can find out more about using ext3 under Linux 2.4 on <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.zip.com.au/~akpm/linux/ext3/ext3-usage.html\">this site</uri>\n"
"maintained by Andrew Morton.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:838
#, no-wrap
msgid "To create ReiserFS filesystems, use the <c>mkreiserfs</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:841
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating ReiserFS filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:842
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mkreiserfs /dev/hda3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:848
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating XFS and JFS filesystems"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:852
#, no-wrap
msgid "To create an XFS filesystem, use the <c>mkfs.xfs</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:855
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating XFS filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:856
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mkfs.xfs /dev/hda3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:860
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You may want to add a couple of additional flags to the mkfs.xfs command: <c>-d\n"
"agcount=3 -l size=32m</c>. The <c>-d agcount=3</c> command will lower the\n"
"number of allocation groups. XFS will insist on using at least one\n"
"allocation group per 4GB of your partition, so, for example, if you have a 20GB\n"
"partition you will need a minimum agcount of 5. The <c>l size=32m</c> command\n"
"increases the journal size to 32MB, increasing performance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:869
#, no-wrap
msgid "To create JFS filesystems, use the <c>mkfs.jfs</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:872
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating JFS filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:873
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mkfs.jfs /dev/hda3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:879
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mounting filesystems"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:883
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once the filesystem is created, we can mount it using the <c>mount</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:886
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mounting filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:887
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount /dev/hda3 /mnt</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:891
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To mount a filesystem, specify the partition block device as a first argument\n"
"and a \"mountpoint\" as a second argument. The new filesystem will be \"grafted\n"
"in\" at the mountpoint. This also has the effect of \"hiding\" any files that were\n"
"in the <path>/mnt</path> directory on the parent filesystem. Later, when the\n"
"filesystem is unmounted, these files will reappear. After executing the mount\n"
"command, any files created or copied inside <path>/mnt</path> will be stored on\n"
"the new ReiserFS filesystem you mounted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:901
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's say we wanted to mount our boot partition inside <path>/mnt</path>. We\n"
"could do this by performing the following steps:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:905
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mounting boot partition in /mnt"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:906
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>mkdir /mnt/boot</i>\n"
"# <i>mount /dev/hda1 /mnt/boot</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:911
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, our boot filesystem is available inside /mnt/boot. If we create files\n"
"inside <path>/mnt/boot</path>, they will be stored on our ext3 filesystem that\n"
"physically resides on <path>/dev/hda1</path>. If we create file inside\n"
"<path>/mnt</path> but not <path>/mnt/boot</path>, then they will be stored on\n"
"our ReiserFS filesystem that resides on <path>/dev/hda3</path>. And if we\n"
"create files outside of <path>/mnt</path>, they will not be stored on either\n"
"filesystem but on the filesystem of our current Linux system or boot disk.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:921
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To see what filesystems are mounted, type <c>mount</c> by itself. Here is the\n"
"output of <c>mount</c> on one of our currently-running Linux system, which has\n"
"partitions configured identically to those in the example above:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:926
#, no-wrap
msgid "Output of mount command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:927
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"/dev/root on / type reiserfs (rw,noatime)\n"
"none on /dev type devfs (rw)\n"
"proc on /proc type proc (rw)\n"
"tmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw)\n"
"usbdevfs on /proc/bus/usb type usbdevfs (rw)\n"
"/dev/hde1 on /boot type ext3 (rw,noatime)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:936
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also view similar information by typing cat <path>/proc/mounts</path>.\n"
"The \"root\" filesystem, <path>/dev/hda3</path> gets mounted automatically by the\n"
"kernel at boot-time, and gets the symbolic name <path>/dev/hda3</path>. On our\n"
"system, both <path>/dev/hda3</path> and <path>/dev/root</path> point to the\n"
"same underlying block device using a symbolic link:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:943
#, no-wrap
msgid "Symbolic links"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:944
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>ls -l /dev/root</i>\n"
"lr-xr-xr-x   1 root   root   33 Mar 26 20:39 /dev/root -> ide/host0/bus0/target0/lun0/part3\n"
"\n"
"# <i>ls -l /dev/hda3</i>\n"
"lr-xr-xr-x   1 root   root   33 Mar 26 20:39 /dev/hde3 -> ide/host0/bus0/target0/lun0/part3\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:954
#, no-wrap
msgid "Even more mounting stuff"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:958
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So, what is this \"<path>/dev/ide/host0</path>....\" file? Systems like mine that\n"
"use the devfs device-management filesystem for <path>/dev</path> have longer\n"
"official names for the partition and disk block devices than Linux used to have\n"
"in the past. For example, <path>/dev/ide/host0/bus1/target0/lun0/part7</path>\n"
"is the official name for <path>/dev/hdc7</path>, and <path>/dev/hdc7</path>\n"
"itself is just a symlink pointing to the official block device. You can\n"
"determine if your system is using devfs by checking to see if the\n"
"<path>/dev/.devfsd</path> file exists; if so, then devfs is active.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:969
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When using the mount command to mount filesystems, it attempts to auto-detect\n"
"the filesystem type. Sometimes, this may not work and you will need to specify\n"
"the to-be-mounted filesystem type manually using the -t option, as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:974
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mounting ext3 filesystem manually with -t option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:975
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount /dev/hda1 /mnt/boot -t ext3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:978
#, no-wrap
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:980
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mouting reiserfs filesystem manually with -t option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:981
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount /dev/hda3 /mnt -t reiserfs</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:987
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mount options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:991
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It's also possible to customize various attributes of the to-be-mounted\n"
"filesystem by specifying mount options. For example, you can mount a filesystem\n"
"as \"read-only\" by using the \"ro\" option:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:996
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mouting filesystem as read-only"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:997
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount /dev/hdc6 /mnt -o ro</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1001
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With <path>/dev/hdc6</path> mounted read-only, no files can be modified in\n"
"<path>/mnt</path> -- only read. If your filesystem is already mounted\n"
"\"read/write\" and you want to switch it to read-only mode, you can use the\n"
"\"remount\" option to avoid having to unmount and remount the filesystem again:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1007
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using remount option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1008
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount /mnt -o remount,ro</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1012
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Notice that we didn't need to specify the partition block device because the\n"
"filesystem is already mounted and <c>mount</c> knows that <path>/mnt</path> is\n"
"associated with <path>/dev/hdc6</path>. To make the filesystem writeable again,\n"
"we can remount it as read-write:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1018
#, no-wrap
msgid "Remounting filesystem as read-write"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1019
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount /mnt -o remount,rw</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1023
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Note that these remount commands will not complete successfully if any process\n"
"has opened any files or directories in <path>/mnt</path>. To familiarize\n"
"yourself with all the mount options available under Linux, type <c>man\n"
"mount</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1032
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing fstab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1036
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So far, we've seen how partition an example disk and mount filesystems manually\n"
"from a boot disk. But once we get a Linux system installed, how do we configure\n"
"that Linux system to mount the right filesystems at the right time?  For\n"
"example, Let's say that we installed Gentoo Linux on our current example\n"
"filesystem configuration. How would our system know how to to find the root\n"
"filesystem on <path>/dev/hda3</path>? And if any other filesystems -- like swap\n"
"-- needed to be mounted at boot time, how would it know which ones?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1046
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Well, the Linux kernel is told what root filesystem to use by the boot loader,\n"
"and we'll take a look at the linux boot loaders later in this tutorial. But for\n"
"everything else, your Linux system has a file called <path>/etc/fstab</path>\n"
"that tells it about what filesystems are available for mounting. Let's take a\n"
"look at it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1056
#, no-wrap
msgid "A sample fstab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1060
#, no-wrap
msgid "Let's take a look at a sample <path>/etc/fstab</path> file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1063
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sample /etc/fstab file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1064
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  &lt;fs&gt; &lt;mountpoint&gt; &lt;type&gt;    &lt;opts&gt;            &lt;dump/pass&gt;\n"
"\n"
"/dev/hda1       /boot           ext3            noauto,noatime          1 1\n"
"/dev/hda3       /               reiserfs        noatime                 0 0\n"
"/dev/hda2       none            swap            sw                      0 0\n"
"/dev/cdrom      /mnt/cdrom      iso9660         noauto,ro,user          0 0\n"
"# /proc should always be enabled\n"
"proc            /proc           proc            defaults                0 0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1075
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Above, each non-commented line in <path>/etc/fstab</path> specifies a partition\n"
"block device, a mountpoint, a filesystem type, the filesystem options to use\n"
"when mounting the filesystem, and two numeric fields. The first numeric field\n"
"is used to tell the <c>dump</c> backup command the filesystems that should be\n"
"backed up. Of course, if you are not planning to use <c>dump</c> on your\n"
"system, then you can safely ignore this field. The last field is used by the\n"
"<c>fsck</c> filesystem integrity checking program, and tells it the order in\n"
"which your filesystems should be checked at boot. We'll touch on <c>fsck</c>\n"
"again in a few panels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1087
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Look at the <path>/dev/hda1</path> line; you'll see that <path>/dev/hda1</path>\n"
"is an ext3 filesystem that should be mounted at the <path>/boot</path>\n"
"mountpoint. Now, look at <path>/dev/hda1</path>'s mount options in the opts\n"
"column. The noauto option tells the system to not mount <path>/dev/hda1</path>\n"
"automatically at boot time; without this option, <path>/dev/hda1</path> would\n"
"be automatically mounted to <path>/boot</path> at system boot time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1096
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Also note the noatime option, which turns off the recording of atime (last\n"
"access time) information on the disk. This information is generally not needed,\n"
"and turning off atime updates has a positive effect on filesystem performance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1102
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, take a look at the <path>/proc</path> line and notice the defaults option.\n"
"Use defaults whenever you want a filesystem to be mounted with just the\n"
"standard mount options. Since <path>/etc/fstab</path> has multiple fields, we\n"
"can't simply leave the option field blank.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1109
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Also notice the <path>/etc/fstab</path> line for <path>/dev/hda2</path>. This\n"
"line defines <path>/dev/hda2</path> as a swap device. Since swap devices aren't\n"
"mounted like filesystems, none is specified in the mountpoint field. Thanks to\n"
"this <path>/etc/fstab</path> entry, our <path>/dev/hda2</path> swap device will\n"
"be enabled automatically when the system starts up.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With an <path>/etc/fstab</path> entry for <path>/dev/cdrom</path> like the one\n"
"above, mounting the CD-ROM drive becomes easier. Instead of typing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1121
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mounting CD-ROM without entry in fstab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1122
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount -t iso9660 /dev/cdrom /mnt/cdrom -o ro</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1126
#, no-wrap
msgid "We can now type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1129
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mounting CD-ROM with entry in fstab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1130
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>mount /dev/cdrom</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In fact, using <path>/etc/fstab</path> allows us to take advantage of the user\n"
"option. The user mount option tells the system to allow this particular\n"
"filesystem to be mounted by any user. This comes in handy for removable media\n"
"devices like CD-ROM drives. Without this fstab mount option, only the root user\n"
"would be able to use the CD-ROM drive.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1144
#, no-wrap
msgid "Unmounting filesystems"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1148
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Generally, all mounted filesystems are unmounted automatically by the system\n"
"when it is rebooted or shut down. When a filesystem is unmounted, any cached\n"
"filesystem data in memory is flushed to the disk.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1154
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, it's also possible to unmount filesystems manually. Before a\n"
"filesystem can be unmounted, you first need to ensure that there are no\n"
"processes running that have open files on the filesystem in question. Then, use\n"
"the <c>umount</c> command, specifying either the device name or mount point as\n"
"an argument:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1161
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1169
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using umount command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1162
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>umount /mnt</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1166
#, no-wrap
msgid "or\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1170
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>umount /dev/hda3</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1174
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once unmounted, any files in <path>/mnt</path> that were \"covered\" by the\n"
"previously-mounted filesystem will now reappear.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1181
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing fsck"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1185
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If your system crashes or locks up for some reason, the system won't have an\n"
"opportunity to cleanly unmount your filesystems. When this happens, the\n"
"filesystems are left in an inconsistent (unpredictable) state. When the system\n"
"reboots, the <c>fsck</c> program will detect that the filesystems were not\n"
"cleanly unmounted and will want to perform a consistency check of filesystems\n"
"listed in <path>/etc/fstab</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1194
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For a filesystem to be checked by <c>fsck</c> it must have a non-zero number in\n"
"the \"pass\" field (the last field) in <path>/etc/fstab</path>. Typically, the\n"
"root filesystem is set to a passno of 1, specifying that it should be checked\n"
"first. All other filesystems that should be checked at startup time should have\n"
"a passno of 2 or higher. For some journaling filesystems like ReiserFS, it is\n"
"safe to have a passno of 0 since the journaling code (and not an external\n"
"<c>fsck</c>) takes care of making the filesystem consistent again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1204
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Sometimes, you may find that after a reboot <c>fsck</c> is unable to fully\n"
"repair a partially damaged filesystem. In these instances, all you need to do\n"
"is to bring your system down to single-user mode and run <c>fsck</c> manually,\n"
"supplying the partition block device as an argument. As <c>fsck</c> performs\n"
"its filesystem repairs, it may ask you whether to fix particular filesystem\n"
"defects. In general, you should say <c>y</c> (yes) to all these questions and\n"
"allow <c>fsck</c> to do its thing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1216
#, no-wrap
msgid "Problems with fsck"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1220
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One of the problems with <c>fsck</c> scans is that they can take quite a while\n"
"to complete, since the entirety of a filesystem's metadata (internal data\n"
"structure) needs to be scanned in order to ensure that it's consistent. With\n"
"extremely large filesystems, it is not unusual for an exhaustive fsck to take\n"
"more than an hour.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1228
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In order to solve this problem, a new type of filesystem was designed, called a\n"
"journaling filesystem. Journaling filesystems record an on-disk log of recent\n"
"changes to the filesystem metadata. In the event of a crash, the filesystem\n"
"driver inspects the log. Because the log contains an accurate account of recent\n"
"changes on disk, only these parts of the filesystem metadata need to be checked\n"
"for errors. Thanks to this important design difference, checking a journalled\n"
"filesystem for consistency typically takes just a matter of seconds, regardless\n"
"of filesystem size. For this reason, journaling filesystems are gaining\n"
"popularity in the Linux community. For more information on journaling\n"
"filesystems, see the <uri\n"
