#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1466
#, no-wrap
msgid "About this section"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1470
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This section introduces the Linux boot procedure. We'll cover the concept of a\n"
"boot loader, how to set kernel options at boot, and how to examine the boot log\n"
"for errors. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1478
#, no-wrap
msgid "The MBR"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1482
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The boot process is similar for all machines, regardless of which distribution\n"
"is installed. Consider the following example hard disk:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1486
#, no-wrap
msgid "Structure of a hard disk"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1487
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"+----------------+\n"
"|      MBR       |\n"
"+----------------+\n"
"|  Partition 1:  |\n"
"| Linux root (/) |\n"
"|   containing   |\n"
"|   kernel and   |\n"
"|     system.    |\n"
"+----------------+\n"
"|  Partition 2:  |\n"
"|   Linux swap   |\n"
"+----------------+\n"
"|  Partition 3:  |\n"
"|   Windows 3.0  |\n"
"|  (last booted  |\n"
"|    in 1992)    |\n"
"+----------------+\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1507
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"First, the computer's BIOS reads the first few sectors of your hard disk. These\n"
"sectors contain a very small program, called the \"Master Boot Record,\" or\n"
"\"MBR.\" The MBR has stored the location of the Linux kernel on the hard disk\n"
"(partition 1 in the example above), so it loads the kernel into memory and\n"
"starts it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1517
#, no-wrap
msgid "The kernel boot process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1521
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The next thing you see (although it probably flashes by quickly) is a line\n"
"similar to the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1525
#, no-wrap
msgid "Boot process line"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1526
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1708
#, no-wrap
msgid "Linux version 2.4.16 (root@time.flatmonk.org) (gcc version 2.95.3 20010315 (release)) #1 Sat Jan 12 19:23:04 EST 2002\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1530
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is the first line printed by the kernel when it starts running. The first\n"
"part is the kernel version, followed by the identification of the user that\n"
"built the kernel (usually root), the compiler that built it, and the timestamp\n"
"when it was built.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1537
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Following that line is a whole slew of output from the kernel regarding the\n"
"hardware in your system: the processor, PCI bus, disk controller, disks, serial\n"
"ports, floppy drive, USB devices, network adapters, sound cards, and possibly\n"
"others will each in turn report their status.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1546
#, no-wrap
msgid "/sbin/init"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1550
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When the kernel finishes loading, it starts a program called <c>init</c>. This\n"
"program remains running until the system is shut down. It is always assigned\n"
"process ID 1, as you can see:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1555
#, no-wrap
msgid "init process ID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1556
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ps --pid 1</i>\n"
"PID TTY          TIME CMD\n"
"  1 ?        00:00:04 init.system\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1562
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>init</c> program boots the rest of your distribution by running a series\n"
"of scripts. These scripts typically live in <path>/etc/rc.d/init.d</path> or\n"
"<path>/etc/init.d</path>, and they perform services such as setting the\n"
"system's hostname, checking the filesystem for errors, mounting additional\n"
"filesystems, enabling networking, starting print services, etc. When the\n"
"scripts complete, <c>init</c> starts a program called <c>getty</c> which\n"
"displays the login prompt, and you're good to go!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1574
#, no-wrap
msgid "Digging in: LILO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1578
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that we've taken a quick tour through the booting process, let's look more\n"
"closely at the first part: the MBR and loading the kernel. The maintenance of\n"
"the MBR is the responsibility of the \"boot loader.\" The two most popular boot\n"
"loaders for x86-based Linux are \"LILO\" (LInux LOader) and \"GRUB\" (GRand Unified\n"
"Bootloader).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1586
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Of the two, LILO is the older and more common boot loader. LILO's presence on\n"
"your system is reported at boot, with the short \"LILO boot:\" prompt. Note that\n"
"you may need to hold down the shift key during boot to get the prompt, since\n"
"often a system is configured to whiz straight through without stopping.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1593
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There's not much fanfare at the LILO prompt, but if you press the &lt;tab&gt;\n"
"key, you'll be presented with a list of potential kernels (or other operating\n"
"systems) to boot. Often there's only one in the list. You can boot one of them\n"
"by typing it and pressing &lt;enter&gt;. Alternatively you can simply press\n"
"&lt;enter&gt; and the first item on the list will boot by default.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1603
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using LILO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1607
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Occasionally you may want to pass an option to the kernel at boot time. Some of\n"
"the more common options are <c>root=</c> to specify an alternative root\n"
"filesystem, <c>init=</c> to specify an alternative init program (such as\n"
"<c>init=/bin/sh</c> to rescue a misconfigured system), and <c>mem=</c> to\n"
"specify the amount of memory in the system (for example <c>mem=512M</c> in the\n"
"case that Linux only autodetects 128M). You could pass these to the kernel at\n"
"the LILO boot prompt:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1616
#, no-wrap
msgid "LILO boot prompt"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1617
#, no-wrap
msgid "LILO boot: linux root=/dev/hdb2 init=/bin/sh mem=512M\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1621
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you need to regularly specify command-line options, you might consider\n"
"adding them to <path>/etc/lilo.conf</path>. The format of that file is\n"
"described in the <path>lilo.conf</path>(5) man-page.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1629
#, no-wrap
msgid "An important LILO gotcha"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1633
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before moving on to GRUB, there is an important gotcha to LILO. Whenever you\n"
"make changes to <path>/etc/lilo.conf</path>, or whenever you install a new\n"
"kernel, you must run <c>lilo</c>. The <c>lilo</c> program rewrites the MBR to\n"
"reflect the changes you made, including recording the absolute disk location of\n"
"the kernel. The example here makes use of the -v flag for verboseness:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
