msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1771
#, no-wrap
msgid "Single-user mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1775
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Recall from the section regarding boot loaders that it's possible to pass\n"
"parameters to the kernel when it boots. One of the most often used parameters\n"
"is <c>s</c>, which causes the system to start in \"single-user\" mode. This mode\n"
"usually mounts only the root filesystem, starts a minimal subset of the init\n"
"scripts, and starts a shell rather than providing a login prompt.\n"
"Additionally, networking is not configured, so there is no chance of external\n"
"factors affecting your work.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1787
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding single-user mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1791
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So what \"work\" can be done with the system in such a state? To answer this\n"
"question, we have to realize a vast difference between Linux and Windows.\n"
"Windows is designed to normally be used by one person at a time, sitting at the\n"
"console. It is effectively always in \"single-user\" mode. Linux, on the other\n"
"hand, is used more often to serve network applications, or provide shell or X\n"
"sessions to remote users on the network. These additional variables are not\n"
"desirable when you want to perform maintenance operations such as restoring\n"
"from backup, creating or modifying filesystems, upgrading the system from CD,\n"
"etc. In these cases you should use single-user mode. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1809
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In fact, it's not actually necessary to reboot in order to reach single-user\n"
"mode. The <c>init</c> program manages the current mode, or \"runlevel,\" for the\n"
"system. The standard runlevels for a Linux system are defined as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1815
#, no-wrap
msgid "0: Halt the computer"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1816
#, no-wrap
msgid "1 or s: Single-user mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1817
#, no-wrap
msgid "2: Multi-user, no network"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1818
#, no-wrap
msgid "3: Multi-user, text console"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1819
#, no-wrap
msgid "4: Multi-user, graphical console"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1820
#, no-wrap
msgid "5: same as 4"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1821
#, no-wrap
msgid "6: Reboot the computer."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1825
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"These runlevels vary between distributions, so be sure to consult your distro's\n"
"documentation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1832
#, no-wrap
msgid "telinit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1836
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To change to single-user mode, use the <c>telinit</c> command, which instructs\n"
"<c>init</c> to change runlevels:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1840
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using telinit command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1841
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>telinit 1</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1845
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can see from the table above that you can also shutdown or reboot the\n"
"system in this manner. <c>telinit 0</c> will halt the computer; <c>telinit\n"
"6</c> will reboot the computer. When you issue the <c>telinit</c> command to\n"
"change runlevels, a subset of the <c>init</c> scripts will run to either shut\n"
"down or start up system services.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1855
#, no-wrap
msgid "Runlevel etiquette"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1859
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, note that this is rather rude if there are users on the system at the\n"
"time (who may be quite angry with you). The <c>shutdown</c> command provides a\n"
"method for changing runlevels in a way that treats users reasonably. Similarly\n"
"to the <c>kill</c> command's ability to send a variety of signals to a process,\n"
"<c>shutdown</c> can be used to halt, reboot, or change to single-user mode. For\n"
"example, to change to single-user mode in 5 minutes:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1867
#, no-wrap
msgid "Changing to single-user mode with 5 minutes delay"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1868
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>shutdown 5</i>\n"
"Broadcast message from root (pts/2) (Tue Jan 15 19:40:02 2002):\n"
"The system is going DOWN to maintenance mode in 5 minutes!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1874
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you press &lt;control-c&gt; at this point, you can cancel the pending switch\n"
"to single-user mode. The message above would appear on all terminals on the\n"
"system, so users have a reasonable amount of time to save their work and log\n"
"off. (Some might argue whether or not 5 minutes is \"reasonable\")\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1883
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"Now\" and halt"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1887
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're the only person on the system, you can use \"now\" instead of an\n"
"argument in minutes. For example, to reboot the system right now:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1891
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using shutdown command with now option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1892
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>shutdown -r now</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1896
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"No chance to hit &lt;control-c&gt; in this case; the system is already on its\n"
"way down. Finally, the -h option halts the system:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1900
#, no-wrap
msgid "Halting the system"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1901
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>shutdown -h 1</i>\n"
"Broadcast message from root (pts/2) (Tue Jan 15 19:50:58 2002):\n"
"The system is going DOWN for system halt in 1 minute!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1909
#, no-wrap
msgid "The default runlevel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1913
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You've probably gathered at this point that the <c>init</c> program is quite\n"
"important on a Linux system. You can configure <c>init</c> by editing the file\n"
"<path>/etc/initttab</path>, which is described in the inittab(5) man-page.\n"
"We'll just touch on one key line in this file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1919
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing init configuration file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1920
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>grep ^id: /etc/inittab</i>\n"
"id:3:initdefault:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1925
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"On my system, runlevel 3 is the default runlevel. It can be useful to change\n"
"this value if you prefer your system to boot immediately into a graphical login\n"
"(usually runlevel 4 or 5). To do so, simply edit the file and change the value\n"
"on that line. But be careful! If you change it to something invalid, you'll\n"
"probably have to employ the <c>init=/bin/sh</c> trick we mentioned earlier.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1939
#, no-wrap
msgid "Additional information related to this section can be found at:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1944
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://www.redhat.com/docs/manuals/linux/RHL-7.2-Manual/ref-guide/s1-init-boot-shutdown-init.html\">\n"
"    Sysvinit docs at Red Hat</uri>\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1949
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://www.linuxdoc.org/LDP/sag/init.html\">Linux System\n"
