#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1959
#, no-wrap
msgid "Filesystem quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1961
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1965
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Quotas are a feature of Linux that let you track disk usage by user or by\n"
"group. They're useful for preventing any single user or group from using an\n"
"unfair portion of a filesystem, or from filling it up altogether. Quotas can\n"
"only be enabled and managed by the root user. In this section, I'll describe\n"
"how to set up quotas on your Linux system and manage them effectively.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1975
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kernel support"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1979
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Quotas are a feature of the filesystem; therefore, they require kernel support.\n"
"The first thing you'll need to do is verify that you have quota support in your\n"
"kernel. You can do this using grep:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1984
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking kernel configuration for quota support"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1985
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>cd /usr/src/linux</i>\n"
"# <i>grep -i quota .config</i>\n"
"CONFIG_QUOTA=y\n"
"CONFIG_XFS_QUOTA=y\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:1992
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If this command returns something less conclusive (such as CONFIG_QUOTA is not\n"
"set) then you should rebuild your kernel to include quota support. This is not\n"
"a difficult process, but is outside of the scope of this section of the\n"
"tutorial. If you're unfamiliar with the steps to build and install a new\n"
"kernel, you might consider referencing this <uri\n"
"link=\"/doc/en/articles/linux-kernel-compiling.xml\">tutorial</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2003
#, no-wrap
msgid "Filesystem support"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2007
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before diving into the administration of quotas, please note that quota support\n"
"on Linux as of the 2.4.x kernel series is not complete. There are currently\n"
"problems with quotas in the ext2 and ext3 filesystems, and ReiserFS does not\n"
"appear to support quotas at all. This tutorial bases its examples on XFS, which\n"
"seems to properly <uri\n"
"link=\"http://oss.sgi.com/projects/xfs/faq.html#quotaswork\">support\n"
"quotas</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2019
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2029
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2023
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To begin configuring quotas on your system, you should edit\n"
"<path>/etc/fstab</path> to mount the affected filesystems with quotas enabled.\n"
"For our example, we use an XFS filesystem mounted with user and group quotas\n"
"enabled:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2030
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>grep quota /etc/fstab</i>\n"
"/usr/users   /mnt/hdc1    xfs    usrquota,grpquota,noauto   0 0\n"
"# <i>mount /usr/users</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2036
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Note that the usrquota and grpquota options don't necessarily enable quotas on\n"
"a filesystem. You can make sure quotas are enabled using the <c>quotaon</c>\n"
"command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2041
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2042
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>quotaon /usr/users</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2046
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There is a corresponding <c>quotaoff</c> command should you desire to disable\n"
"quotas in the future:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2050
#, no-wrap
msgid "Disabling quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2051
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>quotaoff /usr/users</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2055
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"But for the moment, if you're trying some of the examples in this tutorial, be\n"
"sure to have quotas enabled.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2062
#, no-wrap
msgid "The quota command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2066
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>quota</c> command displays a user's disk usage and limits for all of the\n"
"filesystems currently mounted. The -v option includes in the list filesystems\n"
"where quotas are enabled, but no storage is currently allocated to the user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2071
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using quota command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2072
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>quota -v</i>\n"
"\n"
"Disk quotas for user root (uid 0): \n"
"Filesystem  blocks   quota   limit   grace   files   quota   limit   grace\n"
" /dev/hdc1       0       0       0               3       0       0        \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2080
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The first column, blocks, shows how much disk space the root user is currently\n"
"using on each filesystem listed. The following columns, quota and limit, refer\n"
"to the limits currently in place for disk space. We will explain the difference\n"
"between quota and limit, and the meaning of the grace column later on. The\n"
"files column shows how many files the root user owns on the particular\n"
"filesystem. The following quota and limit columns refer to the limits for\n"
"files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2092
#, no-wrap
msgid "Viewing quota"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2096
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Any user can use the <c>quota</c> command to view their own quota report as\n"
"shown in the previous example. However only the root user can look at the\n"
"quotas for other users and groups. For example, say we have a filesystem,\n"
"<path>/dev/hdc1</path> mounted on <path>/usr/users</path>, with two users: jane\n"
"and john. First, let's look at jane's disk usage and limits.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2103
#, no-wrap
msgid "Viewing quota for user"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2104
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>quota -v jane</i>\n"
"\n"
"Disk quotas for user jane (uid 1003): \n"
"Filesystem  blocks   quota   limit   grace   files   quota   limit   grace\n"
" /dev/hdc1    4100       0       0               6       0       0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2112
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this example, we see that jane's quotas are set to zero, which indicates no\n"
"limit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2119
#, no-wrap
msgid "edquota"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now let's say we want to give the user jane a quota. We do this with the\n"
"<c>edquota</c> command. Before we start editing quotas, let's see how much\n"
"space we have available on <path>/usr/users</path>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2128
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking available space on /usr/users"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>df /usr/users</i>\n"
"\n"
"Filesystem           1k-blocks      Used Available Use% Mounted on\n"
"/dev/hdc1               610048      4276    605772   1% /usr/users\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2136
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This isn't a particularly large filesystem, only 600MB or so. It seems prudent\n"
"to give jane a quota so that she can't use more than her fair share. When you\n"
"run <c>edquota</c>, a temporary file is created for each user or group you\n"
"specify on the command line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2143
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>edquota</c> command puts you in an editor, which enables you to add\n"
"and/or modify quotas via this temporary file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2147
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modifying quota"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2148
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>edquota jane</i>\n"
"\n"
"Disk quotas for user jane (uid 1003):\n"
"Filesystem         blocks       soft       hard     inodes     soft     hard\n"
" /dev/hdc1           4100          0          0          6        0        0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2156
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Similar to the output from the <c>quota</c> command above, the blocks and\n"
"inodes columns in this temporary file refer to the disk space and number of\n"
"files jane is currently using. You cannot modify the number of blocks or\n"
"inodes; any attempt to do so will be summarily discarded by the system. The\n"
"soft and hard columns show jane's quota, which we can see is currently\n"
"unlimited (again, zero indicates no quota).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2167
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding edquota"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2171
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The soft limit is the maximum amount of disk usage that jane has allocated to\n"
"her on the filesystem (in other words, her quota). If jane uses more disk\n"
"space than is allocated in her soft limit, she will be issued warnings about\n"
"her quota violation via e-mail. The hard limit indicates the absolute limit on\n"
"disk usage, which a user can't exceed. If jane tries to use more disk space\n"
"than is specified in the hard limit, she will get a \"Disk quota exceeded\"\n"
"error and will not be able to complete the operation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2183
#, no-wrap
msgid "Making changes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2187
#, no-wrap
msgid "So here we change jane's soft and hard limits and save the file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2190
#, no-wrap
msgid "Changed soft and hard limits"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2192
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Disk quotas for user jane (uid 1003):\n"
"Filesystem         blocks       soft       hard     inodes     soft     hard\n"
" /dev/hdc1           4100      10000      11500          6     2000     2500\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2198
#, no-wrap
msgid "Running the <c>quota</c> command, we can inspect our modifications:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2201
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking quota for user jane"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2202
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>quota jane</i>\n"
"\n"
"Disk quotas for user jane (uid 1003): \n"
"Filesystem  blocks   quota   limit   grace   files   quota   limit   grace\n"
" /dev/hdc1    4100   10000   11500               6    2000    2500\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2212
#, no-wrap
msgid "Copying quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2216
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You'll remember that we also have another user, john, on this filesystem. If\n"
"we want to give john the same quota as jane, we can use the -p option to\n"
"<c>edquota</c>, which uses jane's quotas as a prototype for all following users\n"
"on the command line. This is an easy way to set up quotas for groups of users.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2222
#, no-wrap
msgid "Coping quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2223
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>edquota -p jane john</i>\n"
"# <i>quota john</i>\n"
"\n"
"Disk quotas for user john (uid 1003): \n"
"Filesystem  blocks   quota   limit   grace   files   quota   limit   grace\n"
" /dev/hdc1       0   10000   11500               1    2000    2500        \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2234
#, no-wrap
msgid "Group restrictions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2238
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We can also use <c>edquota</c> to restrict the allocation of disk space based\n"
"on the group ownership of files. For example, to edit the quotas for the users\n"
"group:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2243
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing quotas for the users group"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2244
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>edquota -g users</i>\n"
"Disk quotas for group users (gid 100): Filesystem blocks soft hard inodes soft hard /dev/hdc1 4100 500000 510000 7 100000 125000\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2249
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then to view the modified quotas for the users group:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2252
#, no-wrap
msgid "Viewing modified quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2253
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>quota -g users</i>\n"
"Disk quotas for group users (gid 100): Filesystem blocks quota limit grace files quota limit grace /dev/hdc1 4100 500000 510000 7 100000 125000\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2260
#, no-wrap
msgid "The repquota command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2264
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Looking at each users' quotas using the <c>quota</c> command can be tedious if\n"
"you have many users on a filesytem. The <c>repquota</c> command summarizes the\n"
"quotas for a filesystem into a nice report. For example, to see the quotas for\n"
"all users and groups on <path>/usr/users</path>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2270
#, no-wrap
msgid "Summarizing quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2271
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>repquota -ug /usr/users</i>\n"
"*** Report for user quotas on device /dev/hdc1\n"
"Block grace time: 7days; Inode grace time: 7days\n"
"                        Block limits                File limits\n"
"User            used    soft    hard  grace    used  soft  hard  grace\n"
"----------------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"root      --       0       0       0              3     0     0       \n"
"john      --       0   10000   11500              1  2000  2500       \n"
"jane      --    4100   10000   11500              6  2000  2500       \n"
"\n"
"*** Report for group quotas on device /dev/hdc1\n"
"Block grace time: 7days; Inode grace time: 7days\n"
"                        Block limits             File limits\n"
"Group           used    soft    hard  grace    used  soft  hard  grace\n"
"----------------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"root      --       0       0      0               3     0     0       \n"
"users     --    4100  500000 510000               7 100000 125000  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2293
#, no-wrap
msgid "Repquota options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2297
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are a couple of other options to repquota that are worth mentioning.\n"
"<c>repquota -a</c> will report on all currently mounted read-write filesystems\n"
"that have quotas enabled. <c>repquota -n</c> will not resolve uids and gids to\n"
"names. This can speed up the output for large lists.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2306
#, no-wrap
msgid "Monitoring quotas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2310
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you are a system administrator, you will want to have a way to monitor\n"
"quotas to ensure that they are not being exceeded. An easy way to do this is\n"
"to use <c>warnquota</c>. The <c>warnquota</c> command sends e-mail to users who\n"
"have exceeded their soft limit. Typically <c>warnquota</c> is run as a\n"
"cron-job.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2318
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When a user exceeds his or her soft limit, the grace column in the output from\n"
"the <c>quota</c> command will indicate the grace period -- how long before the\n"
"soft limit is enforced for that filesystem.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2323
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking grace period"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2324
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Disk quotas for user jane (uid 1003): \n"
"    Filesystem  blocks   quota   limit   grace   files   quota   limit   grace\n"
"    /dev/hdc1   10800*  10000   11500    7days      7     2000    2500\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2330
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, the grace period for blocks and inodes is seven days.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2336
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modifying the grace period"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2340
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can modify the grace period for filesystems using <c>equota</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2343
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modyfing grace period"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2344
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>edquota -t</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2348
#, no-wrap
msgid "This puts you in an editor of a temporary file that looks like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2351
#, no-wrap
msgid "Looks of a grace editor"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2352
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Grace period before enforcing soft limits for users:\n"
"Time units may be: days, hours, minutes, or seconds\n"
"Filesystem             Block grace period     Inode grace period\n"
"/dev/hdc1                    7days                  7days\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2359
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The text in the file is nicely explanatory. Be sure to leave your users enough\n"
"time to receive their warning e-mail and find some files to delete!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2366
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking quotas on boot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2370
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You may also want to check quotas on boot. You can do this using a script to\n"
"run the <c>quotacheck</c> command; there is an example script in the <uri\n"
"link=\"http://en.tldp.org/HOWTO/Quota.html\">Quota Mini HOWTO</uri>. The\n"
"<c>quotacheck</c> command also has the ability to repair damaged quota files;\n"
"familiarize yourself with it by reading the quotacheck(8) man-page.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2378
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Also remember what we mentioned previously regarding <c>quotaon</c> and\n"
"<c>quotaoff</c>. You should incorporate <c>quotaon</c> into your boot script so\n"
"that quotas are enabled. To enable quotas on all filesystems where quotas are\n"
"supported, use the -a option:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2384
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using -a option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2385
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>quotaon -a</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2393
#, no-wrap
msgid "System logs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2395
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing syslogd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2399
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The syslog daemon provides a mature client-server mechanism for logging\n"
"messages from programs running on the system. Syslog receives a message from a\n"
"daemon or program, categorizes the message by priority and type, then logs it\n"
"according to administrator-configurable rules. The result is a robust and\n"
"unified approach to managing logs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2409
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2421
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reading logs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2413
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's jump right in and look at the contents of a syslog-recorded log file.\n"
"Afterward, we can come back to syslog configuration. The FHS (see <uri\n"
"link=\"/doc/en/articles/lpi-101-administration-p2.xml\">Part 2</uri> of this\n"
"tutorial series) mandates that log files be placed in <path>/var/log</path>.\n"
"Here we use the <c>tail</c> command to display the last 10 lines in the\n"
"\"messages\" file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2422
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>cd /var/log</i>\n"
"# <i>tail messages</i>\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:39 bilbo init: Entering runlevel: 3\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:40 bilbo /usr/sbin/named[337]: starting BIND 9.1.3\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:40 bilbo /usr/sbin/named[337]: using 1 CPU\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:41 bilbo /usr/sbin/named[350]: loading configuration from '/etc/bind/named.conf'\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:41 bilbo /usr/sbin/named[350]: no IPv6 interfaces found\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:41 bilbo /usr/sbin/named[350]: listening on IPv4 interface lo, 127.0.0.1#53\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:41 bilbo /usr/sbin/named[350]: listening on IPv4 interface eth0, 10.0.0.1#53\n"
"Jan 12 20:17:41 bilbo /usr/sbin/named[350]: running\n"
"Jan 12 20:41:58 bilbo gnome-name-server[11288]: starting\n"
"Jan 12 20:41:58 bilbo gnome-name-server[11288]: name server starting\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2437
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You may remember from the text-processing whirlwind that the <c>tail</c>\n"
"command displays the last lines in a file. In this case, we can see that the\n"
"nameserver named was recently started on this system, which is named bilbo. If\n"
"we were deploying IPv6, we might notice that named found no IPv6 interfaces,\n"
"indicating a potential problem. Additionally, we can see that a user may have\n"
"recently started GNOME, indicated by the presence of gnome-name-server.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2448
#, no-wrap
msgid "Tailing log files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2452
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"An experienced system administrator might use <c>tail -f</c> to follow the\n"
"output to a log file as it occurs:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2456
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using tail -f command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2457
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>tail -f /var/log/messages</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2461
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For example, in the case of debugging our theoretical IPv6 problem, running the\n"
"above command in one terminal while stopping and starting named would\n"
"immediately display the messages from that daemon. This can be a useful\n"
"technique when debugging. Some administrators even like to keep a constantly\n"
"running <c>tail -f</c> messages in a terminal where they can keep an eye on\n"
