#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2507
#, no-wrap
msgid "<path>cron</path>: Cron-related messages and errors"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2508
#, no-wrap
msgid "<path>spooler</path>: UUCP and news-related messages and errors."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2514
#, no-wrap
msgid "syslog.conf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2518
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As a matter of fact, now would be a good time to investigate the syslog\n"
"configuration file, <path>/etc/syslog.conf</path>. (Note: If you don't have\n"
"<path>syslog.conf</path>, keep reading for the sake of information, but you may\n"
"be using an alternative syslog daemon.) Browsing that file, we see there are\n"
"entries for each of the common log files mentioned above, plus possibly some\n"
"other entries. The file has the format facility.priority action, where those\n"
"fields are defined as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2528
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"facility: Specifies the subsystem that produced the message. The valid keywords\n"
"for facility are auth, authpriv, cron, daemon, kern, lpr, mail, news, syslog,\n"
"user, uucp and local0 through local7.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2534
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"priority: Specifies the minimum severity of the message, meaning that messages\n"
"of this priority and higher will be matched by this rule. The valid keywords\n"
"for priority are debug, info, notice, warning, err, crit, alert, and emerg.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2540
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"action: The action field should be either a filename, tty (such as\n"
"<path>/dev/console</path>), remote machine prefixed by @ , comma-separated list\n"
"of users, or to send the message to everybody logged on. The most common action\n"
"is a simple filename.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2549
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reloading and additional information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2553
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Hopefully this overview of the configuration file helps you to get a feel for\n"
"the strength of the syslog system. You should read the syslog.conf(5) man-page\n"
"for more information prior to making changes. Additionally the syslogd(8)\n"
"man-page supplies lots more detailed information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2560
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Note that you need to inform the syslog daemon of changes to the configuration\n"
"file before they are put into effect. Sending it a SIGHUP is the right method,\n"
"and you can use the <c>killall</c> command to do this easily:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2565
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using killall command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2566
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>killall -HUP syslogd</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2572
#, no-wrap
msgid "A security note"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2576
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You should beware that the log files written to by syslogd will be created by\n"
"the program if they don't exist. Regardless of your current umask setting, the\n"
"files will be created world-readable. If you're concerned about the security,\n"
"you should chmod the files to be read-write by root only. Additionally, the\n"
"<c>logrotate</c> program (described below) can be configured to create new log\n"
"files with the appropriate permissions. The syslog daemon always preserves the\n"
"current attributes of an existing log file, so you don't need to worry about it\n"
"once the file is created.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2589
#, no-wrap
msgid "logrotate"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2593
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The log files in <path>/var/log</path> will grow over time, and potentially\n"
"could fill the filesystem. It is advisable to employ a program such as\n"
"<c>logrotate</c> to manage the automatic archiving of the logs. The\n"
"<c>logrotate</c> program usually runs as a daily cron job, and can be\n"
"configured to rotate, compress, remove, or mail the log files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2601
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For example, a default configuration of logrotate might rotate the logs weekly,\n"
"keeping 4 weeks worth of backlogs (by appending a sequence number to the\n"
"filename), and compress the backlogs to save space. Additionally, the program\n"
"can be configured to deliver a SIGHUP to syslogd so that the daemon will notice\n"
"the now-empty log files and append to them appropriately.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2609
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For more information on <c>logrotate</c>, see the logrotate(8) man page, which\n"
"contains a description of the program and the syntax of the configuration file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2616
#, no-wrap
msgid "Advanced topic -- klogd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2620
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before moving away from syslog, I'd like to note a couple of advanced topics\n"
"for ambitious readers. These tips may save you some grief when trying to\n"
"understand syslog-related topics.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2626
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"First, the syslog daemon is actually part of the sysklogd package, which\n"
"contains a second daemon called klogd. It's klogd's job to receive information\n"
"and error messages from the kernel, and pass them on to syslogd for\n"
"categorization and logging. The messages received by klogd are exactly the same\n"
"as those you can retrieve using the <c>dmesg</c> command. The difference is\n"
"that <c>dmesg</c> prints the current contents of a ring buffer in the kernel,\n"
"whereas klogd is passing the messages to syslogd so that they won't be lost\n"
"when the ring wraps around.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2639
#, no-wrap
msgid "Advanced topic -- alternate loggers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2643
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Second, there are alternatives to the standard sysklogd package. The\n"
"alternatives attempt to be more efficient, easier to configure, and possibly\n"
"more featureful than sysklogd. <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.balabit.hu/en/downloads/syslog-ng/\">Syslog-ng</uri> and <uri\n"
"link=\"http://metalog.sourceforge.net/\">Metalog</uri> seem to be some of the\n"
"more popular alternatives; you might investigate them if you find sysklogd\n"
"doesn't provide the level of power you need.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-advanced-p4.xml:2653
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Third, you can log messages in your scripts using the logger command. See the\n"
"logger(1) man page for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

